<TEI.2 ID="ch020"><TEIHEADER><FILEDESC><TITLESTMT><TITLE>[Letter] 1824 May 24, Washington, to Colo[nel] Thomas L. McKenney / Jno. [i.e., John] Ross ... [et al.] : a machine-readable transcription</TITLE><AUTHOR>Ross, John, 1790-1866</AUTHOR><AUTHOR>Hicks, Elijah</AUTHOR><AUTHOR>Lowrey, George</AUTHOR><AUTHOR>Ridge, Major,  ca. 1771-1839</AUTHOR><RESPSTMT><RESP>Creation of machine-readable version:</RESP><NAME>Lesli Wall Zimmerman</NAME><NAME>Debra Jean Roney</NAME></RESPSTMT></TITLESTMT><PUBLICATIONSTMT><PUBLISHER>The University of Tennessee Libraries</PUBLISHER><PUBPLACE>Knoxville, TN</PUBPLACE><ADDRESS><ADDRLINE>Hoskins Library - Special Collections</ADDRLINE><ADDRLINE>The University of Tennessee</ADDRLINE><ADDRLINE>Knoxville, TN 37996</ADDRLINE></ADDRESS><DATE>2000</DATE><IDNO>ch020</IDNO><IDNO>OCLC: 44771014</IDNO><AVAILABILITY STATUS="FREE"><P>This work is the property of The Tennessee State Library and Archives, Nashville, TN.  It may be used freely by individuals for research, teaching, and personal use as long as this statement of availability is included in the text.</P></AVAILABILITY></PUBLICATIONSTMT><SOURCEDESC><BIBL><TITLE>[Letter] 1824 May 24, Washington, to Colo[nel] Thomas L. McKenney / Jno. [i.e., John] Ross ... [et al.] </TITLE><AUTHOR>Ross, John, 1790-1866</AUTHOR><AUTHOR>Hicks, Elijah</AUTHOR><AUTHOR>Lowrey, George</AUTHOR><AUTHOR>Ridge, Major, ca. 1771-1839</AUTHOR><DATE VALUE="1824-05-24">May 24,1824</DATE><EXTENT>4p</EXTENT><NOTE TYPE="summary">This document is a letter from a delegation of Cherokee leaders including John Ross, George Lowrey, Major Ridge, and Elijah Hicks, to Colonel Thomas L. McKenney, in the Department of War, dated May 24, 1824.  The  delegation complains to McKenney about the payment of claims of the Cherokees against white intruders who have stolen and/or damaged Cherokee property.  They indicate their dissatisfaction with the response of the U.S. agent, Joseph McMinn, to these claims and insist that the issue be addressed by the War Department.</NOTE><NOTE TYPE="repository">The Tennessee State Library and Archives, Nashville, TN</NOTE><NOTE TYPE="collection">State Library Cherokee Collection</NOTE><NOTE TYPE="box"> 1</NOTE><NOTE TYPE="folder"> 23</NOTE><NOTE TYPE="document">ch020</NOTE></BIBL></SOURCEDESC></FILEDESC><ENCODINGDESC><PROJECTDESC><P>Prepared for The University of Tennessee Digital Library</P></PROJECTDESC><EDITORIALDECL><P>Quotation marks retained as data except inside q tags</P><P>Errors in transcription of the printed text controlled with Microsoft Word spell-checker; text has also been thoroughly proofread.</P><P>Corrections and normalization represented by editorial tags.</P><P>All unambiguous end-of-line hyphens removed. </P><P>Catchwords and directional notes such as "turn page over" have been omitted.</P></EDITORIALDECL><REFSDECL><P>ID attributes provided for only those pages, chapters, or illustrations toward which a reference or figure points</P></REFSDECL><CLASSDECL><TAXONOMY ID="LCSH"><BIBL><TITLE>Library of Congress Subject Headings</TITLE></BIBL></TAXONOMY></CLASSDECL></ENCODINGDESC><PROFILEDESC><TEXTCLASS><KEYWORDS SCHEME="LCSH"><LIST><ITEM>Letters</ITEM><ITEM>Cherokee Indians--Land tenure</ITEM><ITEM>Cherokee Indians--Claims</ITEM><ITEM>McMinn, Joseph, 1758-1824</ITEM><ITEM>Southern States</ITEM></LIST> </KEYWORDS></TEXTCLASS></PROFILEDESC></TEIHEADER><TEXT><BODY><DIV1 TYPE="letter"><PB N="[1]"><OPENER><DATELINE><ADDRESS><ADDRLINE><NAME TYPE="place">Washington City</NAME> <NAME TYPE="place">Tennison's Hotel</NAME></ADDRLINE></ADDRESS><DATE VALUE="1824-05-24">May 24th. 1824.</DATE></DATELINE><LB><ADDRESS><ADDRLINE>To <NAME TYPE="person"><ABBR EXPAN="Colonel Thomas">Colo. Thos.</ABBR> L. McKenney</NAME></ADDRLINE><ADDRLINE>War <ABBR EXPAN="Department Indian">Deptmt. Ind.</ABBR> Office</ADDRLINE></ADDRESS><SALUTE>Friend &amp; Brother</SALUTE></OPENER><P>We herewith submit before the War Department a list containing sundry <NAME TYPE="person">Cherokee</NAME> Claims for property <ORIG REG="destroyed">distroyed</ORIG>, taken or stolen from them, by citizens of the <NAME TYPE="place">United States</NAME>, they were rendered in to us on the <DEL TYPE="overstrike">leaving</DEL> eve of our leaving the Nation for this place, under a strong hope that we should have been enabled to have had them disposed of by the government together with those which are now and for many years past been before the War Department; The most of this property it appears has been taken by the intruders, such are the bad effects, under which the <NAME TYPE="person">Cherokees</NAME> <ORIG REG="labor">labour</ORIG> from this lawless class of your citizens, they <DEL TYPE="overstrike"><UNCLEAR>chose</UNCLEAR></DEL> are not only ravaged of their property, but every species of vice tending to demoralize the character of man, are introduced <DEL TYPE="overstrike">among</DEL><PB N="[2]"> by them; as may naturally be supposed, its influence like a contagious disease, has in some extent prevailed among the lower class of our citizens; and it is with all the difficulties and exertion under which a skillful physician necessarily <ORIG REG="labor">labour</ORIG> in such a case, that the Nation are anxiously striving to suppress it; but unless the Government under its solemn obligations establish a strict quarantine on the boundaries; The Nation can be but partially successful in preventing the obnoxious evils arising <DEL TYPE="overstrike">from</DEL> <ADD PLACE="supralinear">by</ADD> intrusions, from spreading&mdash;.</P><P>These claims may in some particular be found deficient of positive proofs but this is owing in a great degree to the peculiar disadvantage in which the Indians are placed, being ignorant of the laws of the <NAME TYPE="place">United States</NAME> and not having any other evidence than Indians, and likewise unacquainted with the necessary rules &amp; forms by which to establish their claims, they can but go to the person most convenient to them, who can write, and there relate the circumstances attending their loss, and should the person who undertake to make out their claims, prove to be awkward <DEL TYPE="overstrike">and</DEL><PB N="[3]">and unacquainted with business, it is imperfectly done; under <DEL TYPE="overstrike">these</DEL> such disadvantageous circumstances, has these claims been stated and rendered in to us; and which ought to be borne in mind by those who may have to investigate them; they were not rendered in to the agent, as is usual because the claimants apprehended that they might be laid over like other claims, for a long time before they would be acted upon; and as they had anticipated as we have already mentioned, that we should have been enabled at this time to have had them disposed of&mdash;  We therefore now submit them with a hope that they, together with those which have for many <ADD PLACE="supralinear">years</ADD> been awaiting the adjudication of the War Department may be disposed of as practicable&mdash;</P><CLOSER><SALUTE>We have the Honor to be respectfully<LB>Your friends &amp; Brothers</SALUTE></CLOSER><CLOSER><SIGNED><NAME TYPE="person"><ABBR EXPAN="John">Jno</ABBR> Ross</NAME></SIGNED><SIGNED><NAME TYPE="person"><ABBR EXPAN="George">Geo..</ABBR> Lowrey</NAME></SIGNED><SIGNED><NAME TYPE="person">Major Ridge</NAME></SIGNED> his<SIGNED>X</SIGNED> mark<SIGNED><NAME TYPE="person">Elijah Hicks</NAME></SIGNED></CLOSER></DIV1></BODY><BACK><DIV1 TYPE="letter"><PB N="[4]"><P><NAME TYPE="place">Washington City</NAME> <DATE VALUE="1824-05-24">May 24th 1824</DATE><LB><NAME TYPE="person">Cherokee</NAME> Delegation, East <NAME REG="River" TYPE="place">Mississippi</NAME>.<LB>Submitting sundry claims for property taken from the Indians by Citizens of the <NAME TYPE="place">U. States</NAME>.</P></DIV1><DIV1 TYPE="letter"><P><ADDRESS><ADDRLINE><NAME TYPE="person"><ABBR EXPAN="Colonel">Colo.</ABBR> Thomas L. McKenney</NAME></ADDRLINE><ADDRLINE>Indian Office</ADDRLINE><ADDRLINE>War Department</ADDRLINE></ADDRESS></P></DIV1></BACK></TEXT></TEI.2>
